{"type":null,"faqId":26427,"title":"Ten Photo Taking Tips","answer":"<p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:center\" align=\"center\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';\ncolor:#333333\">Ten Photo Taking Tips</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Smartphones' photo-taking capabilities are getting more\nand more advanced. Some smartphones are even better than compact cameras. This\ndocument provides some tips to help you take stunning photos with your phone. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;text-indent:21.0pt;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-top:0in;margin-right:0in;\nmargin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:.25in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Microsoft YaHei','sans-serif';\ncolor:black;\"><span>1.<span style=\"font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n</span></span></span></b><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Keep your phone steady. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Smartphones are light and can be easily shaken, because\nof which photos will be blurred. Keep your phone when holding it, especially\nwhen your phone does not support optical image stabilization. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">2. Do not use digital zoom. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Digital zoom will decrease the photo quality. To crop\nyour photos, use the built-in photo editing application on your phone. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">3. Use the best resolution and aspect ratio. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Go to the settings menu of the camera, and choose the\nhighest resolution. The Honor 6 Plus adopts a 16:9 light sensor that can take\nwide-screen photos. For other phones, choose the 4:3 aspect ratio. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">4. Regularly wipe the camera lens with a piece of soft\ncloth. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">5. Adjust the focus and exposure by touching the\nviewfinder. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">If you find the exposure is inaccurate or the photo is\nout of focus, simply touch the object you are shooting on the viewfinder. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">6. Use the trisecting method. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Trisecting is an easy way for composing a photo. Trisect\nthe viewfinder using your eyes or the gridlines on your phone, and place the object\nyou are shooting along the vertical line, or a crosspoint of vertical and\nhorizontal lines. Make sure the ground is parallel with the horizontal line. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">7. Learn about different capture modes. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Most smartphones provide a variety of photo-taking functions.\nFor example, you can remove a moving object from the photo or add special\neffects. Different capture modes are available that allow you to take photos\nwith different styles without manual configuration.</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">8. Try third-party camera applications. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Developers provide all kinds of third-party camera\napplications for Android phones, iPhones, or Windows phones. These applications\nbring many other functions that are unavailable in the built-in camera. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">9. Take multiple photos at a time for selection. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">No matter you are taking photos using a phone or camera,\ntake multiple photos at a time so you can have alternative photos if someone\nblinks his or her eyes or the photos get blurred.</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">10. Edit the photos to a reasonable extent. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:left;\n\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:black;\n\">Filters can bring an artistic sense to your photos when\nproperly used. Do not overly apply filters to avoid aesthetic fatigue. Other\ngood methods for editing your photos are adjusting the contrast and brightness\nand cropping the photos. </span></b></p>\n<br>\n</p>","faqTypeId":null,"faqType":null,"useful":0,"unUseful":0,"languageId":1,"languageName":"en","faqCode":"826","faqTypeCode":null,"isTop":"0","moduleCode":"faq","productId":null,"productCode":null,"postDate":1433165227000,"seriesProductName":"","visitedTimes":6,"isUsefulFlag":null,"score":0,"times":0,"imageList":null,"displayType":"text","justView":"0","fileName":null,"filePath":null,"imagePath":null,"imageName":null,"productIdList":null,"curPage":null,"pageSize":null,"siteCode":null,"statusFlag":"Publish","returnCode":0,"totalRows":null,"keywords":"Ten Photo Taking Tips","avgScore":0.0,"createDate":null,"totalPages":null}